The better world is already here.
COPENHAGEN – For centuries, optimists and pessimists have debated the state of the world.
Pessimists see a world in which more people mean less food, in which increasing resource demand leads to exploitation and war, and in which the growing production capacity of recent decades results in more pollution and global warming.
One of the holy texts of the current generation of pessimists, "The Limits to Growth," continues to influence the environmental movement to this day.
The optimists, on the other hand, claim that everything gets better – human health, the standard of living, environmental quality, and so on.
They are seen by their opponents as "economists of abundance," who trust the market, which is supposedly able to solve all problems.
But instead of picking out facts and stories that fit into a grand narrative of decline or progress, we should try to compare all aspects of human existence to see whether the world is really getting better or worse.
Exactly this I have tried to achieve together with 21 internationally leading economists by developing a rating list of the last 150 years.
In ten areas – including health, education, war, gender ratios, air pollution, climate change, and biodiversity – economists have answered the same question: What were the relative costs of this problem each year from 1900 to 2013, including projections up to 2050.
Using classical economic evaluations of all factors—from deaths, health damages, and illiteracy to the destruction of wetlands and increased hurricane risk due to global warming—economists demonstrate the costs of each individual problem.
To assess the scale of the problem, it is compared with the overall available resources for its solution.
This makes it clear how significant the problem is as a share of GDP.
And the trends since 1900 are partly surprising.
Let us consider the inequality of the sexes.
In essence, we excluded almost half of the world's population from production back then.
In 1900 were only 15% of the global workforce female.
What are the losses resulting from this small share?
Even though we take into account the higher costs due to women's education and the fact that someone must perform unpaid housework, the losses amounted to at least 17% of the world's GDP in 1900.
Today, with a higher female labor participation rate and smaller income gaps, the loss is 7% – and is likely to fall to 4% by 2050.
It is likely to be very surprising that climate change from 1900 to 2025 is expected to largely provide a growing net benefit – which could rise up to 1.5% of GDP annually.
This is due to the different effects of global warming. If it occurs only moderately, the benefits outweigh the drawbacks.
On the one hand, the higher CO2 emissions were a blessing for agriculture, as the gas acts as a fertilizer. This is the largest positive effect, amounting to 0.8% of GDP.
Similarly, a moderate warming prevents more cold-related deaths than it causes additional heat-related deaths.
It also reduces the heating demand more than it creates new cooling demand, which corresponds to a benefit of about 0.4% of GDP.
On the other hand, warming leads to water shortages, which cost about 0.2% of GDP, and has a negative impact on ecosystems such as wetlands, corresponding to a loss of about 0.1%.
However, as temperatures continue to rise, the costs increase and the benefits decrease, which dramatically reduces the net benefit.
After 2070, global warming will cause net costs to the world, which justifies cost-effective climate protection today and in the coming decades.
However, the ranking also shows us that the largest environmental problem worldwide is indoor air pollution, which puts things into the right perspective.
Today, more than three million people die each year from indoor air pollution caused by harmful emissions from cooking and heating. This corresponds to a loss of 3% of the world's GDP.
But in the year 1900, these costs accounted for 19% of GDP, and it is expected that they will drop to 1% by 2050.
Health indicators have improved the most around the world.
Until the late 18th century, human life expectancy had hardly changed.
The size of the profit since 1900 can hardly be overemphasized: At that time, the global life expectancy was 32 years, and today it is 69 years (and by 2050 it is likely to be 76 years).
The biggest influencing factor was the decline in child mortality.
For example, as late as 1970, only 5% of infants were vaccinated against measles, tetanus, whooping cough, diphtheria, and polio.
In the year 2000, it was 85%, which led to the saving of three million lives every year – more than would have been saved in the entire 20th century through world peace.
This success has many parents.
The Gates Foundation and the GAVI Alliance have spent more than $2.5 billion on vaccines and have pledged an additional $10 billion.
Through the efforts of the Rotary Club, the World Health Organization, and many others, cases of polio have been reduced by 99% since 1979.
In economic terms, the costs of poor health at the beginning of the twentieth century amounted to astonishing 32% of the world's GDP.
Today they have dropped to about 11% and are expected to halve again by 2050.
Even though optimists are not entirely correct in all points (the loss of biodiversity in the twentieth century probably costs about 1% of GDP annually, and in some places significantly more), the overall picture is clear.
Most of the examined topics show improvements of 5-20% of GDP.
And the general trend is even more pronounced.
Relative to the resources available for their combat, global problems have dramatically decreased.
Of course, this does not mean that there are no more problems.
Although they have become smaller in the areas of health, education, malnutrition, air pollution, gender inequality, and trade, they are still large.
But realists should gradually get used to the idea that the world has improved significantly.
In addition, the ranking list shows us where the challenges for a better 2050 lie.
We should not base our view of the future on the worst stories or the loudest interest groups, but rather on objective assessments of the areas where we can achieve the greatest improvements.
